<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:ExternalAngles.svg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/5/51/ExternalAngles.svg/330px-ExternalAngles.svg.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"245" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"744" data-file-height=3D"588"></a><figcaption>Internal and extern=
al angles</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry"=
>geometry</a>, an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"=
Angle">angle</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" tit=
le=3D"Polygon">polygon</a> is formed by two adjacent <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_(geometry)" title=3D"Edge (geometry)">sides</a>.  F=
or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simp=
le polygon">simple polygon</a> (non-self-intersecting), regardless of wheth=
er it is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon#Convexity_and_non=
-convexity" title=3D"Polygon">convex or non-convex</a>, this angle is calle=
d an <b>internal angle</b> (or interior angle) if a point within the angle =
is in the interior of the polygon. A polygon has exactly one internal angle=
 per <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_(geometry)" title=3D"V=
ertex (geometry)">vertex</a>.
</p><p>If every internal angle of a simple polygon is less than a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Straight_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Straight angle">straight angle</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Pi" title=3D"Pi"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">=CF=80</span></a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian" =
title=3D"Radian">radians</a> or 180=C2=B0), then the polygon is called <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygo=
n">convex</a>.
</p><p>In contrast, an <b>external angle</b> (also called a turning angle o=
r exterior angle) is an angle formed by one side of a simple polygon and a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_side" title=3D"Extended s=
ide">line extended from an adjacent side</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PL_1-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_and_ext=
ernal_angles#cite_note-PL-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Page / location: pp. 261=E2=80=93264">:=E2=80=8App. 261=E2=80=93=
264=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Properties">Properties</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternal_and_ext=
ernal_angles&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Prop=
erties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<ul><li>The sum of the internal angle and the external angle on the same ve=
rtex is <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</s=
pan> radians (180=C2=B0).</li>
<li>The sum of all the internal angles of a simple polygon is <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=80</i>(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2)</span> radians or <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">180(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2)</span> degrees, where <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is the number of si=
des. The formula can be proved by using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematical_induction" title=3D"Mathematical induction">mathematical=
 induction</a>: starting with a triangle, for which the angle sum is 180=C2=
=B0, then replacing one side with two sides connected at another vertex, an=
d so on.</li>
<li>The sum of the external angles of any simple polygon, if only one of th=
e two external angles is assumed at each vertex, is <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>2<i>=CF=80</i></span> radians (360=C2=B0).</li>
<li>The measure of the exterior angle at a vertex is unaffected by which si=
de is extended: the two exterior angles that can be formed at a vertex by e=
xtending alternately one side or the other are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Vertical_angles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vertical angle=
s">vertical angles</a> and thus are equal.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extension_to_crossed_polygo=
ns">Extension to crossed polygons</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DInternal_and_external_angles&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Extension to crossed polygons"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The interior angle concept can be extended in a consistent way to <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossed_polygon" title=3D"Crossed polygo=
n">crossed polygons</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St=
ar_polygon" title=3D"Star polygon">star polygons</a> by using the concept o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDirected_angles&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Directed angles (p=
age does not exist)">directed angles</a>. In general, the interior angle su=
m in degrees of any closed polygon, including crossed (self-intersecting) o=
nes, is then given by <span class=3D"texhtml">180(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2<i>k<=
/i>)=C2=B0</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">n</span> is the number of vertices, and the strictly positive integ=
er <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is th=
e number of total (360=C2=B0) revolutions one undergoes by walking around t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perimeter_of_the_polygon" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Perimeter of the polygon">perimeter</a> of the po=
lygon. In other words, the sum of all the exterior angles is <span class=3D=
"texhtml">2<i>=CF=80k</i></span> radians or <span class=3D"texhtml">360<i>k=
</i></span> degrees. Example: for ordinary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Convex_polygon" title=3D"Convex polygon">convex polygons</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concave_polygon" title=3D"Concave p=
olygon">concave polygons</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D 1</span>=
, since the exterior angle sum is 360=C2=B0, and one undergoes only one ful=
l revolution by walking around the perimeter.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extension_to_polyhedra">Ext=
ension to polyhedra</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DInternal_and_external_angles&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Extension to polyhedra"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descartes%27_=
theorem_on_total_angular_defect" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Descartes' =
theorem on total angular defect">Descartes' theorem on total angular defect=
</a></div>
<p>Consider a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron" title=3D=
"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a> that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Homeomorphism" title=3D"Homeomorphism">topologically equivalent</a> to a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a=
>, such as any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polytope" ti=
tle=3D"Convex polytope">convex polyhedron</a>.  Any vertex of the polyhedro=
n will have several <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Facet_(geometr=
y)" title=3D"Facet (geometry)">facets</a> that meet at that vertex.  Each o=
f these facets will have an interior angle at that vertex and the sum of th=
e interior angles at a vertex can be said to be the interior angle associat=
ed with that vertex of the polyhedron.  The value of <span class=3D"texhtml=
">2<i>=CF=80</i></span> radians (or 360 degrees) minus that interior angle =
can be said to be the exterior angle associated with that vertex, also know=
n by other names such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_d=
efect" title=3D"Angular defect">angular defect</a>.  The sum of these exter=
ior angles across all vertices of the polyhedron will necessarily be <span =
class=3D"texhtml">4<i>=CF=80</i></span> radians (or 720 degrees), and the s=
um of the interior angles will necessarily be <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>=
=CF=80</i>(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2)</span> radians (or <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>360(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2)</span> degrees) where <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is the number of vertices.  A proo=
f of this can be obtained by using the formulas for the sum of interior ang=
les of each facet together with the fact that the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Euler_characteristic" title=3D"Euler characteristic">Euler =
characteristic</a> of a sphere is 2.
</p><p>For example, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectangular_=
solid" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rectangular solid">rectangular solid<=
/a> will have three rectangular facets meeting at any vertex, with each of =
these facets having a 90=C2=B0 internal angle at that vertex, so each verte=
x of the rectangular solid is associated with an interior angle of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">3 =C3=97 90=C2=B0 =3D 270=C2=B0</span> and an exterior angl=
e of <span class=3D"texhtml">360=C2=B0 =E2=88=92 270=C2=B0 =3D 90=C2=B0</sp=
an>.  The sum of these exterior angles over all eight vertices is <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">8 =C3=97 90=C2=B0 =3D 720=C2=B0</span>.  The sum of these in=
terior angles over all eight vertices is <span class=3D"texhtml">8 =C3=97 2=
70=C2=B0 =3D 2160=C2=B0</span>.
</p>
